title: For Sale:  CZ CZECH CZ 27 EARLY HIGH POLISH GERMAN ARMY ISSUE (ICN8279)
postcontent: We have an early production, .32 ACP, 75% blue, mint CZ 27 (vz. 27) pistol in good condition. This is one of the most beautiful early high polish CZ 27 pistols we have ever seen. Perfect mechanical condition, and an excellent like new bore. Serial Number: 110,307. This pistol has the original high polish blue finish, strawed small parts (straw color is very generous), and is fitted with original one piece checkered Bakelite (early plastic) excellent grips with no cracks or chips, with the “ČZ” logos molded on the top. The pistol is housed in an original leather flap CZ 27 holster displaying a Nazi-German Military “eagle/WaA76” WaffenAmt acceptance mark (on the back). The pistol is complete with an original factory magazine stamped on the bottom of the base “P. Mod. 27”. This is a rather common WW2 German-issued pistol in uncommonly nice condition. CZ 27 was one of the most widely-issued non-German pocket pistols of WW2. They are extremely well-made and overbuilt. While most CZ 27 variants are quite common, it is difficult to find early pistols like this one in such exceptional condition. This is the high polish variant, made to the highest quality. The finish on early CZ 27 pistols, with serial numbers ranging from 20,500 to 230,000, was bright blue. As the production progressed, the finish changed to dull blue, then to half blue and half phosphate, and finally to all phosphate. This pistol displays a Nazi-German Military “eagle/WaA 76” WaffenAmt acceptance mark (on right frame, top slide, and barrel). The barrel is stamped with an “eagle clutching a swastika” German Military test proof mark. The top of the slide is marked “BÖHMISCHE WAFFENFABRIK A.G. IN PRAG” (Česká zbrojovka [CZ] in Prague) followed by the Nazi proof and serial number. Left side of the slide is marked “Pistole Modell 27 Kal. 7,65”. All the numbered parts are matching (right on frame, top of slide, left on side plate, and on barrel). In March 1939, Germany occupied all of Czechoslovakia, and in early 1941, all CZ 27 pistol production was diverted to the German war effort. Czechoslovak sources put the beginning serial number of German Military production at 20,500 (the serial number of our early pistol is 110,307). Between 620,000 and 650,000 CZ 27 pistols were manufactured in total, 452,500 of those under German occupation.To buy or call >>>> CZ CZECH CZ 27 EARLY HIGH POLISH GERMAN ARMY ISSUE

This is the high polish variant, made to the highest quality. The finish on early CZ 27 pistols, with serial numbers ranging from 20,500 to 230,000, was bright blue. As the production progressed, the finish changed to dull blue, then to half blue and half phosphate, and finally to all phosphate. This pistol displays a Nazi-German Military “eagle/WaA 76” WaffenAmt acceptance mark (on right frame, top slide, and barrel). The barrel is stamped with an “eagle clutching a swastika” German Military test proof mark. The top of the slide is marked “BÖHMISCHE WAFFENFABRIK A.G. IN PRAG” (Česká zbrojovka [CZ] in Prague) followed by the Nazi proof and serial number. Left side of the slide is marked “Pistole Modell 27 Kal. 7,65”. All the numbered parts are matching (right on frame, top of slide, left on side plate, and on barrel). In March 1939, Germany occupied all of Czechoslovakia, and in early 1941, all CZ 27 pistol production was diverted to the German war effort. Czechoslovak sources put the beginning serial number of German Military production at 20,500 (the serial number of our early pistol is 91,845). Between 620,000 and 650,000 CZ 27 pistols were manufactured in total, 452,500 of those under German occupation. The pistol is complete with an original factory magazine stamped on the bottom of the base “P. Mod. 27”. This pistol has the original high polish blue finish, strawed small parts (straw color is generous), and is fitted with original one piece checkered Bakelite (early plastic) good-quality grips with the “ČZ” logos molded on the top. CZ 27 was one of the most widely-issued non-German pocket pistols of WW2. They are extremely well-made and overbuilt. The pistol is housed in an original leather flap holster.To buy or call >>>>> CZ CZECH CZ 27 EARLY HIGH POLISH GERMAN ARMY ISSUE

title: For Sale:  1942 Remington 1903
postcontent: This is a Remington 1903 (not Springfield, and not the 1903A3 or A4 with the rear mounted sight) in 30.06.  Has original May of 1942 barrel 4 groove barrel (some of the later 1903s had a 2 groove barrel). Barrel has some minor pitting as many of the old originals do, but grooves appears intact. Bayonet included, dated 1943 with "AFH" for American Fork and Hoe, along with US and bomb proof.  Scabbard has US and bomb proof as well.  The rifle has all the correct "R" markings that I can see.  Stock is one of the more rare "scant" stocks, not quite a "C" stock and not a straight stock.  Stock is quite nice, other than the usual small signs of wear, has a couple of places that appear where it was kept in a rifle stand or some such.  But I'm a stickler for detail, the stock has no cracks, no markings of any kind I can see (some of the scant stocks had no markings).  Sling is a reproduction marked "MILSCO 1942".  I have shot this rifle, works as it should, I can't relate it's accuracy as I only test fired it with a few rounds of M2 ball I had on hand, used it as a display for my WW2 collection.

title: For Sale:  CZECH CZ 27 EARLY HIGH POLISH GERMAN ARMY ISSUE (ICN8278)
postcontent: We have an early production, .32 ACP, 65% blue, two-toned, CZ 27 (vz. 27) pistol. The finish is nice, but shows some browning coming through the high polish. Serial Number: 61,321. This is the high polish variant, made to the highest quality. The finish on early CZ 27 pistols, with serial numbers ranging from 20,500 to 230,000, was bright blue. As the production progressed, the finish changed to dull blue, then to half blue and half phosphate, and finally to all phosphate. This pistol displays a Nazi-German Military “eagle/WaA 76” WaffenAmt acceptance mark (on right frame, top slide, and barrel). The barrel is stamped with an “eagle clutching a swastika” German Military test proof mark. The top of the slide is marked “BÖHMISCHE WAFFENFABRIK A.G. IN PRAG” (Česká zbrojovka [CZ] in Prague) followed by the Nazi proof and serial number. Left side of the slide is marked “Pistole Modell 27 Kal. 7,65”. All the numbered parts are matching (right on frame, top of slide, left on side plate, and on barrel). In March 1939, Germany occupied all of Czechoslovakia, and in early 1941, all CZ 27 pistol production was diverted to the German war effort. Czechoslovak sources put the beginning serial number of German Military production at 20,500 (the serial number of our early pistol is 61,321). Between 620,000 and 650,000 CZ 27 pistols were manufactured in total, 452,500 of those under German occupation. The pistol is complete with an original factory magazine stamped on the bottom of the base “P. Mod. 27”. This pistol has the original high polish blue finish, strawed small parts (straw color is generous), and is fitted with original one piece checkered Bakelite (early plastic) good grips, with the “ČZ” logos molded on the top. What makes this pistol so attractive is that the slide has turned a very nice reddish plum color that makes this pistol very attractive and appealing to the eye. CZ 27 was one of the most widely-issued non-German pocket pistols of WW2. They are extremely well-made and overbuilt. The pistol is housed in an original leather flap holster.To buy or call >>>> CZ CZECH CZ 27 EARLY HIGH POLISH GERMAN ARMY ISSUE

The right side forward web of the trigger guard exhibits the Czechoslovak commercial proof mark of a lion over the letter “N” with a two digit date “42” (1942) underneath. The first German Police pistols show up in the 30,000 serial number range produced in late 1941. These pistols are scarce and rarely encountered. This is the high polish variant, made to the highest quality. The finish on early CZ 27 pistols, with serial numbers ranging from 20,500 to 230,000, was bright blue. title: For Sale:  CZ CZECH CZ 27 EARLY HIGH POLISH GERMAN ARMY ISSUE (ICN8275)
postcontent: We have an early production, .32 ACP, 75-80% blue, CZ 27 (vz. 27) pistol in great condition. The bore is bright and shiny. The pistol shows some holster wear. Serial Number: 134,060. This pistol has the original high polish blue finish, strawed small parts, and is fitted with original one piece checkered Bakelite (early plastic) excellent grips with no cracks or chips, with the “ČZ” logos molded on the top. The pistol is housed in an original leather flap CZ 27 holster. The pistol is complete with an original factory magazine stamped on the bottom of the base “P. Mod. 27”. CZ 27 was one of the most widely-issued non-German pocket pistols of WW2. They are extremely well-made and overbuilt. This is the high polish variant, made to the highest quality. The finish on early CZ 27 pistols, with serial numbers ranging from 20,500 to 230,000, was bright blue. As the production progressed, the finish changed to dull blue, then to half blue and half phosphate, and finally to all phosphate. This pistol displays a Nazi-German Military “eagle/WaA 76” WaffenAmt acceptance mark (on right frame, top slide, and barrel). The barrel is stamped with an “eagle clutching a swastika” German Military test proof mark. The top of the slide is marked “BÖHMISCHE WAFFENFABRIK A.G. IN PRAG” (Česká zbrojovka [CZ] in Prague) followed by the Nazi proof and serial number. Left side of the slide is marked “Pistole Modell 27 Kal. 7,65”. All the numbered parts are matching (right on frame, top of slide, left on side plate, and on barrel). In March 1939, Germany occupied all of Czechoslovakia, and in early 1941, all CZ 27 pistol production was diverted to the German war effort. Czechoslovak sources put the beginning serial number of German Military production at 20,500 (the serial number of our early pistol is 134,060). Between 620,000 and 650,000 CZ 27 pistols were manufactured in total, 452,500 of those under German occupation.To buy or call >>>> CZ CZECH CZ 27 EARLY HIGH POLISH GERMAN ARMY ISSUE
